	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />For now I am OK with Windows 7 in Classic theme, even if I miss the shemes like Rainy Day, it doesn't kill the OS or anything.<br /><br />There were several things that were horrible by default but I changed them back to normal, i.e. no title in status bar, big icons, etc... My only complaint is the start menu which can't be brought like it was before, which should really be optional. However I really got used to the new way, you just type the name of the program you want to launch and it finds it, it is quite convenient, more than searching through an unsorted list of 100+ programs. And don't say it's my fault for not sorting it - I had to do that with the PC I had on the campus which were not installed by me, and since they have all programs potentially used by students in the start menu, you get the idea...<br /><br />Linux in itself is fine, but it falls short as soon as you have to do <strong>anything</strong> exotic... like... programming the NES ?<br />Just do a search on RHDN, there is 583 utilities for Windows, but 8 for Unix... this speaks for itself. You could also use some of the 20 which runs with Java, though, so that would make it 603 vs 28, which means there is around 21.5 times more tools for Windows than for Linux.<br />Of course you could also use Wine, but if you go that far why not just use Windows ?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


