		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Found some time for a thread that is really something that annoyed me for a while!<br /><br />I guess engineer with time goes for what is practical instead of the fluffy/shinny stuff.  I was able to use windows 7 for a while at work with all the bell and whistle but I got tired and reverted back to classic mode since it was more practical in general.  Then I tried for fun windows 8, laughed, laughed some more then uninstalled it <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /><br /><br />Koitsu:<br /><br />Regarding the font inside the control panel, there is a registry hack that allow you to put priority to the tahoma font (like windows XP) instead of Segoe UI. If you do that, the font will look crisp. There is still some font left &quot;broken&quot; in some dialog boxes, which I'm sure are still using Segoe UI because of WPF, but I didn't find a solution yet since I didn't have anymore time to put on this. I shouldn't have to go that far to bring back the classic mode like doing a registry hack to remove the annoying pop-up when putting my mouse over an app in a task bar. Maybe this thread is talking about the Segoe UI hack or is a good start:<br /><br /><a href="http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_7-desktop/disable-all-font-smoothing-in-windows-7-ie/f180e803-3317-4433-8fd2-63aadaecc2d2?page=2" class="postlink">http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_7-desktop/disable-all-font-smoothing-in-windows-7-ie/f180e803-3317-4433-8fd2-63aadaecc2d2?page=2</a><br /><br />Since windows 8 this summer, I started to do something at work that I never imagined would because I have been using Microsoft OS since DOS 4.0: A Mac.  I had no choice because of a smartphone project. After trying windows 8, Mac OSX is not that bad after all. They may have done a lot of crap to the OS since Lion (it seems that Snow Leopard is their version of Windows XP) but it still not as bad as Windows 8.  At the least, the smoothed font looks a lot better than Clear type. For some reason, clear type looks like crap on some monitor (of course, the one I have at home) but not other. I don't have that problem with Mac OSX.  Even though I'm not a Mac fanatic, the OS is starting to get interesting compared to win8 and it future offspring.  The only reason I use Lion is because xCode requires it... That so Microsofish. Snow Leopard in other case is more than enough.<br /><br />I tried linux once in a while with every new version of Fedora and everytime I start to configure the UI in KDE or wathever, I always find a way to crash X windows. Maybe it's because of Fedora but still... That kinds of turned me off. And don't propose unbutu, for some reason, I don't like it. The only Windows Manager I liked was XFCE (I think). I got tired about linux because I always had to figure out what to configure next to make something work, because it never worked well every time you try to install something (dependencies, whatever).<br /><br />Since I never really been a Mac fan and I'm now becoming one, the end of the world thing in 2012 must be true then!...<br /><br />I was able to build ca65 on it, now I need to figure out what other tools to use. I may start another thread someday on the subject but I'm in no rush since I cannot work on my projects anyway!<br /><br />Edit:<br /><br />I just saw that mikejmoffitt posted just at the same time as me. His font look better in the control panel than the result I had. Maybe it could be related to asian font or something, like in windows XP? In window XP, if you do install asian font, it has quite an impact on the look of many UI elements.

		

