e</em> a derail, as by now, Xfce is probably the best choice among widely used desktop environments for people who want something remotely similar to Windows XP through 7.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I love installing OS and play with them, I just don't have much time these days for &quot;that kind of geeky fun&quot;</div><br />I'm glad I rediscovered Linux in a brief moment when I had time for geeky fun. On a whim, I tried to get Puppy working on a hideously obsolete laptop, and then when a relative's computer broke, I used Puppy to get it at least browsing the web until it could be repaired. Once the new hard drive was in place, I installed Ubuntu, and that computer is still in service as my cousin's home server.

		

