	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />While I dislike a lot of design choices/mistakes that went into the GUI of every version of every OS I've used, honestly I've found all of them quite functional.<br /><br />I'm not saying it's not worth complaining about (for instance, things that force cleartype on really anger me), but my choice of operating system is held hostage to concerns that don't really have much to do with little GUI details. I work on the OS that supports the software I need to use, or is my target platform for work, etc. If I had a choice I'd use Linux, but I don't have that choice, really.<br /><br />Because of this, there's not much ability to vote with my wallet. Maybe if they started selling micro-features of an OS for small amounts of money, there'd be a better feedback loop, I dunno. (That situation sounds ridiculous as I suggest it, though.) You can complain on forums or whatever, but I think most development effort is focused elsewhere besides fixing the myriad of minor UI issues, so the message might even be getting through, but probably there's not much priority on it.<br /><br />Thankfully though, I don't find it hard to get actual work done in any OS I've tried. I have yet to see one that  I think actually impedes workflow significantly, though they all can be very frustrating at times (and of course, switching to an unfamiliar OS will usually slow you down until you learn how to get around it). The core stuff that lets you get to the software you want to use is generally pretty decent in any OS, because it has to be, otherwise the platform is probably doomed.<br /><br />I also find it funny that Microsoft usually chooses to do a big UI rewrite to make each version of Windows look &quot;new&quot; I guess. Sadly very new implementation has as many faults as the old. I'd appreciate it if they stopped doing that and started fixing the little things incrementally with each version, but I think they believe it's better for business to do it the other way.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
